## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` now throws at runtime on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected — DSA still works there (though it's considered legacy everywhere).

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** existing signatures (not create new ones), you have two options:

**Option A — Platform guard (minimal change):**
If you must keep verifying legacy DSA signatures, gate on the platform and only run DSA verification on Linux/Windows:

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification is not supported on macOS in .NET 11+.");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
// ... verify signature
```

**Option B — Migrate to ECDSA/RSA (recommended long-term):**
Re-sign your data with a modern algorithm and verify with that going forward:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
var signature = ecdsa.SignData(data, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

If the legacy DSA signatures are from an external system you can't re-sign, Option A with a platform guard is the pragmatic fix — just ensure your macOS CI/CD doesn't exercise that code path without the guard.
